	<clause id="scls_2-3" obligation="normative"><title>Solid Solution / Liquid Solution</title><p id="_7b4b22b1-b490-4e16-ab70-24da61f43d4c">When solid solutions of a fixed-point material and its impurities are formed (solid solution / liquid solution), three distinct conditions of segregation of the components can occur during freezing (diffusion in the solid phase can usually be neglected) <eref type="inline" bibitemid="gilman1963" citeas="[32]"/>: Complete mixing, partial mixing, and no mixing in the liquid. In the latter two cases, non-equilibrium effects have to be considered. In practice, several non-equilibrium effects affect the distribution of impurities. These include diffusion, convection, and the non-uniform advancement of the interface due to the formation of particular crystalline structures <eref type="inline" bibitemid="sloan1988" citeas="[83]"/>.</p>
	<p id="_143dd8be-5cb4-40c2-845e-e95d6111d1fc">For fixed-point realisations, diffusion effects are particularly significant. The time taken for impurities to fully diffuse and equilibrate over distances of many millimetres in the liquid phase is usually tens of hours. Consequently, the shape and temperature range of freezing plateaus can depart significantly from the equilibrium curves. The effects of convection are insignificant because of the very small temperature gradients in the sample volume. Considering the typical order of magnitude of the diffusion coefficients <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>D</mi></mstyle></math></stem> in liquid metals (<stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mrow><mo>−</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow></mrow></msup><mtext> </mtext><mstyle mathvariant="normal"><mrow><mi>c</mi><mi>m</mi></mrow></mstyle><mo>/</mo><mstyle mathvariant="normal"><mi>s</mi></mstyle></math></stem>), the case of complete mixing is approximated only at very small rates of freezing, i.e., at very low velocities <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mi>v</mi></math></stem> of the liquid/solid interface (<stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mi>v</mi><mi>l</mi><mo>/</mo><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>D</mi></mstyle><mo>&lt;</mo><mo>&lt;</mo><mn>1</mn></math></stem>, where <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mi>l</mi></math></stem> is the length of the sample in the freezing direction, i.e., the direction of solid growth). Thus, for the experimental conditions normally realized, the results must be analysed carefully to determine whether the segregation of the impurities is in accordance with the strongest possible dependence given by <xref target="eq5"/> below.</p>
	<clause id="scls_2-3-1" obligation="normative"><title>Complete mixing in the liquid</title><p id="_c614704e-cb8c-4762-97c3-9ccba1fe79e5">For this case, it is assumed that freezing is slow enough for complete and uniform mixing (resulting from convection and diffusion of the impurities in the liquid phase) to preclude concentration gradients in the liquid. This leads to the maximum possible segregation of the impurities, and the dependence of <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>T</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mtext>obs</mtext></mrow></msub></math></stem> on <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>F</mi></mstyle></math></stem> is given by the following equation based on the Gulliver-Scheil model <eref type="inline" bibitemid="gulliver1913" citeas="[34]"/>, <eref type="inline" bibitemid="scheil1942" citeas="[82]"/>, <eref type="inline" bibitemid="pfann1966" citeas="[74]"/></p>
	<formula id="eq5">
	<stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>T</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mtext>pure</mtext></mrow></msub><mo>−</mo><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>T</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mtext>obs</mtext></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mo>−</mo><munder><mrow><mo>∑</mo></mrow><mrow><mi>i</mi></mrow></munder><msubsup><mrow><mi>m</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mi>i</mi></mrow></msubsup><msubsup><mrow><mi>c</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mi>i</mi></mrow></msubsup><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>F</mi></mstyle></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mo>−</mo><munder><mrow><mo>∑</mo></mrow><mrow><mi>i</mi></mrow></munder><msubsup><mrow><mi>m</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mi>i</mi></mrow></msubsup><msubsup><mrow><mi>c</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>11</mn></mrow><mrow><mi>i</mi></mrow></msubsup><msup><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>F</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mrow><msubsup><mrow><mi>k</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn></mrow><mrow><mi>i</mi></mrow></msubsup><mi>−</mi><mn>1</mn></mrow></mrow></msup><mi>.</mi></math></stem>
